turns an empty result. Invoke the full service entry point with a list of 4 addresses including the failing one. Assert: (1) the returned route contains exactly 3 stops (the successful addresses), (2) the skipped-addresses report contains exactly the one failing address, (3) the optimizer was invoked with only the 3 successful coordinate sets.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate addresses are consolidated into a single stop with combined delivery items, not visited twice","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The deduplication step — normalizing duplicate address strings, merging their delivery-item lists, and producing a deduplicated stop list — is a self-contained transformation applied before geocoding. The failure ('visited twice') would be observable directly on the output of that transformation function without invoking the geocoder or optimizer. REAL-INFRA: No. MOCK-HIDE: No external dependency; inputs are plain address+items structs. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No. REJECTION-GATE: Integration was considered. It would only be required if deduplication were done post-geocoding (detecting same coordinates for slightly different address strings), which would require the geocoding client to be wired in. The behavior description says 'duplicate addresses' — implying string-level identity — so deduplication can and should be caught at the pure-function level. If an implementation chooses coordinate-level deduplication, the minimum level rises to Integration; under the stated behavior, Unit is sufficient and Integration is a contingent escalation.","test_description":"Call the address-deduplication function directly with a list of stops where two entries share an identical address string but carry different delivery items. Assert: (1) the returned stop list has one fewer entry than the input, (2) the consolidated stop's delivery-item list is the union of both input item lists, (3) a third unique address is unchanged. Also test with three identical addresses to confirm n-way consolidation, and with no duplicates to confirm the passthrough case.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.62,"Integration":0.33,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9589,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9589},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"360161e9-96b9-4527-bbae-a03469a1d054","uuid":"0367036a-4372-4f91-a71a-2946fb64a7c9"}
